Copy everything below this line, paste it into Claude Code, and replace the competitor list and your channel handle with your own.

---

I want you to build a complete YouTube niche analysis system. Here's what I need:

My competitors (replace with your own):
- @channel1
- @channel2
- @channel3
- @channel4
- @channel5
- @channel6
- @channel7
- @channel8
(add as many as you want, 8-15 is ideal)

My own channel: @my_channel_handle

What to do:

Phase 1: Scrape all competitor videos

For EACH competitor channel, one at a time (never batch multiple channels in one call):

Use the Apify YouTube Channel Scraper (actor ID: 67Q6fmd8iedTVcCwY).

API call: POST https://api.apify.com/v2/acts/67Q6fmd8iedTVcCwY/runs?token=$APIFY_API_KEY&waitForFinish=120

Request body: {"startUrls": [{"url": "https://www.youtube.com/@handle"}], "maxResults": 50, "maxResultsShorts": 0}

Save each channel's results to a separate JSON file in a folder called "raw-data".

Important: Only scrape ONE channel per API call. Never put multiple channels in startUrls. The maxResults limit is shared across all channels, so batching gives you incomplete data that looks correct but is wrong.

Also scrape my own channel the same way.


Phase 2: Find outlier videos

For each channel, detect outlier videos using local median comparison:

For each video, look at the 5 videos before and 5 videos after it by upload date. Calculate the median views of those 10 neighbors. If the video got 2x or more views than that local median, it's an outlier.

This method is important because it accounts for channel growth over time. A video with 5,000 views is an outlier if the channel was averaging 2,000 at that time, even if the channel now averages 50,000.

Save the outlier analysis as a JSON file per channel.


Phase 3: Classify all videos

Classify each video by:

Topic: What is the video about? Examples: "Claude Code", "n8n", "AI automation", "vibe coding", "personal brand", "AI agents", "content creation", "freelancing", etc. Use whatever topics fit the niche.

Title pattern: What kind of title is it? Examples: "tutorial", "listicle", "personal story", "hype/contrarian", "tool review", "case study", "challenge/experiment", "comprehensive course", etc.

Format: What type of video is it? Tutorial, course, reaction, vlog, review, or other.

Save all classifications to a JSON file.


Phase 4: Get transcripts of top outliers

For the top 15-20 outlier videos (the ones with the highest outlier ratio across all channels):

Use the Apify YouTube Transcript Scraper (actor ID: faVsWy9VTSNVIhWpR).

API call: POST https://api.apify.com/v2/acts/faVsWy9VTSNVIhWpR/runs?token=$APIFY_API_KEY&waitForFinish=60

Request body: {"videoUrl": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VIDEO_ID"}

Extract the first 500 words of each transcript. This is the hook and intro, which is the most valuable part to study.

Save all transcripts to a "transcripts" folder.


Phase 5: Deep channel analysis

For each competitor channel, write a detailed analysis covering:

1. Content formula: What's their repeating pattern? What do they keep coming back to?

2. What works: Specific titles, formats, and topics that consistently outperform their average. Include concrete examples with view counts.

3. What doesn't work: Content that underperforms their average. What topics or formats fall flat?

4. Audience needs: What problems does this creator solve for their viewers? What do people come to this channel for?

5. Unique angle: What sets this creator apart from everyone else in the niche?

6. Evolution: How has their content changed over the last 12 months? Are they shifting topics, formats, or style?

Save the deep analysis as a JSON file.


Phase 6: Analyze my channel

Do the same full analysis on my channel. Then compare my performance to competitors:

What am I doing that works? Which of my videos outperform and why?
What am I missing that competitors are crushing?
Where's the gap between my content and what the audience clearly wants?
What could I start doing tomorrow based on what the data shows?


Phase 7: Generate the HTML report

Create a clean, professional HTML report and save it as niche-analysis-report.html. Include these sections:

1. Executive summary: The key findings in 3-4 sentences. What's the single most important insight?

2. Numbers at a glance: Total videos analyzed, outliers found, channels studied, transcripts read. Show these as big numbers at the top.

3. Actionable tips: The top 10-15 specific things I should do, scored using the ICE framework. Impact (1-10): how much will this move the needle? Confidence (1-10): how sure are we this will work based on the data? Ease (1-10): how easy is this to implement? Sort by total ICE score, highest first. Each tip should have a clear action, the reasoning from the data, and specific examples.

4. Topic performance: Which topics produce the most outliers? Show as a table with topic name, number of videos, number of outliers, outlier rate, and average views.

5. Title pattern analysis: Which title formats get the most views? Same table format.

6. Top 30 outlier videos: The best-performing videos across all competitors with title, channel, view count, outlier ratio, and link.

7. Thumbnail patterns: What do the top-performing thumbnails have in common? Analyze colors, text, faces, composition.

