Download the zip file from the provided Google Drive link. Drag and drop the zip file into the upload screen. Don't unzip it — just double-click the zip file directly and Claude will handle the rest. The skill installs automatically.
To use it in any conversation, just type: "Start the Offer Clarity Framework skill." That's all it needs.
Step 2: Prepare Your Four Inputs
The skill needs four blocks of information from you. The more specific you are here, the better the output. Vague inputs will get you vague outputs, and Claude will stop and ask clarifying questions before it proceeds — by design.
1. ICP Psychographic Details
Upload or paste your ICP psychographic document (from the Desire Finder skill). This covers your target audience's daily problems, frustrations, desired outcomes, and psychological motivations.
2. Demographic Details
Write out:
Job title (e.g., CMO)
Industry (e.g., AI cold email automation — companies like Smartlead, Instantly, Apollo)
Company size and revenue range
Location / countries
Seniority level (C-suite, VP, Director, Head of, etc.)
3. Your Business Details
Tell Claude about your own company:
Company name
What you do
How long you've been operating
Case studies, proof points, client results
Team size and capabilities
4. Your Product and Offer Details
Be specific here:
Exact deliverables
Timeline
Pricing
What makes your approach different (your unique mechanism)
Any guarantees
Example of a specific offer: "A complete cold outbound plus inbound content strategy to bring high-intent leads." Even that can go deeper — the skill will push you to be more precise.
Step 3: Answer Claude's Clarifying Questions
Once you submit your inputs, if anything is too vague or missing, Claude will stop and ask specific questions. It will not guess and move forward — it's instructed to wait for your answers.
Answer these directly. The more specific your answers, the better the offer document that comes out on the other side. This is not friction — it's the skill doing its job.
Step 4: Review the Offer Document
Claude will generate a full offer clarity document. Here's what each section does and why it matters:
Section 1 — The Problem Statement
This section defines the exact problem your offer solves. Two layers:
What is going wrong?
Not a surface-level pain — the real operational breakdown. Example: "Outbound produces reply volume but not demo bookings. Reply-to-demo conversion sits below 8%. Inbound generates near-zero organic leads, making the pipeline 95% dependent on outbound and paid channels."
What is this problem costing them?
Quantified consequences. Example: "CAC has risen 30% over 12 months. A $500K–$2M monthly pipeline target is being missed or swinging 60% month to month. The CMO is spending time writing campaign copy — something she shouldn't be doing."
This section is the foundation of your cold email hook. If you can say the prospect's problem back to them more precisely than they can say it themselves, you've already won half the battle.
Section 2 — The Outcome
What exactly happens when your offer works? This section makes the outcome specific, measurable, and time-bound.
Example: "We help CMOs hit 40+ qualified demo bookings per month from outbound within 90 days, while building a LinkedIn content engine that generates ICP-sourced inbound leads — without the CMO writing a single sequence brief or post herself. Guaranteed by a defined meeting-booked milestone at day 45."
Notice: there's a number, a timeline, and a guarantee. That's what makes an outcome real. No deliverable lists. The CMO doesn't trust deliverables — she trusts demo bookings on her calendar.
Section 3 — Why They Haven't Fixed It Yet
This is where most people don't think hard enough. Your prospect has had this problem for a while. Why haven't they solved it?
Claude breaks this into barriers:
Primary barrier — Risk/Trust
They've already paid 2-3 agencies and nothing moved the pipeline. Every failed vendor experiment makes them more skeptical and more protective of the budget. Your offer needs to lead with a specific, measurable milestone at a defined date — not a list of things you'll do.
Secondary barrier — Effort
In many cases, the ICP is the only person who can actually run the execution. Every new vendor creates more work before it creates less. Your offer needs to remove the CMO from the day-to-day.
AI Era barrier
In 2024-2025, the objection is: "We can do this in-house with AI." The CMO's team has already used Smartlead and Clay. The real gap isn't capability — it's ICP research, angle identification, and sequence architecture. Your offer needs to address that gap explicitly.
Section 4 — The Tiered Offer Stack
The skill generates three pricing tiers — the same structure you see on most SaaS pricing pages:
Tier 1 (Entry) — Small commitment, low risk, low price. Gets the prospect in the door.
Tier 2 (Core) — Full engagement, monthly retainer, 3-month commitment.
Tier 3 (Premium) — Maximum scope, longest term, highest price.
Each tier includes deliverables, what the client doesn't have to do, and what's excluded. This structure gives your prospect a choice rather than a binary yes/no decision.
Section 5 — The Objection Map
For your specific offer and ICP, Claude maps out the most common objections you will face and drafts response frameworks. Example:
Objection: "We already tried a cold email agency and it didn't work."Response direction: The previous agency sent volume without ICP research. Here's how this is different.
Use this as a starting point, not a script. Rewrite the responses in your own voice. The value here is that you're not blindsided on a sales call — you've already thought through every likely pushback.
Section 6 — Positioning
How to describe what you do across different touchpoints:
LinkedIn headline
Cold email opening line
Cold call pitch
Who this offer is for
Who this offer is NOT for
What makes it different from other options
This section tells you how to show up consistently in your content and outreach.
Section 7 — The Complete Offer Summary
One clean summary block: your ICP, your offer, the price, the problem you solve, the outcome, the proof points. Copy-paste ready for use in a proposal, a Notion doc, or a sales deck.
Step 5: Run the AI Era Stress Test
This is the most useful part that most people skip.
After generating the offer document, Claude will ask you to choose from a few options. One of them is the AI Era Stress Test. Choose it.
What happens: Claude reads your entire offer document as a skeptical CMO — your actual ICP — and tells you exactly where the deal falls apart. It highlights every choke point, every unanswered question, every reason the prospect would say no.
Example output from the stress test: "The CMO's thought: 'My junior can do this with Claude on a Friday afternoon. What am I actually paying for?'"
That's a real objection you'll face. The stress test forces you to answer it before your prospect asks it. You then go back and patch those holes — add a guarantee, reframe the unique mechanism, tighten the pricing logic, or add a specific milestone that removes the risk.
Step 6: Iterate
This is not a one-pass workflow. After getting the initial output, push further:
"Based on my offer, what other problems could this ICP be facing that I'm not addressing?"
"Go deeper on the AI era objection. What specific fears does the CMO have about hiring an agency in this environment?"
"Rewrite the outcome section to be more specific about the 90-day milestone."
"Enhance the positioning section — how should I differentiate from agencies that also claim to do cold outbound?"
Each iteration makes the offer document tighter. The goal is an offer so specific and so well-reasoned that when you put it in front of the right person, the only honest answer is yes.
The Actual Point
You could spend 20 minutes writing a generic offer and start sending cold emails tomorrow. Most people do that. Most people get ignored.
This skill exists to make you think through your offer the way a sharp consultant would — problem, outcome, barriers, objections, positioning, stress test. By the time you finish this process, you understand your own offer better than most agencies understand theirs.
That understanding is what makes your cold email land differently. Not the template. Not the subject line. The clarity of thought behind it.
